<br>
For experience campng, i only used earth pets when necessary.  Whenever possible I would use a fire pet.  The damage shield is free which lowers downtime and is great damage that we need not out do with nukes.  Also, we have an advantage against certain casting mobs and ae mobs because of our pet immunities.  This seems to effect mage life later, but it is often useful that fire is immune to fire damage, water to poison, etc...  Those immunities can help mitigate damage which is very important to soloing.  The key with soloing is to make efficient use of all your resources.  Fire pets save mana, and are immune to fire nukes.  With a fire pet all i have to do is make sure i kill the mob fast which is usually not a problem if it is beating itself to death on my pet.<br>
<br>
Water pets are good tanks that can handle a lot more hits than a fire pet, but there benefit with efficiency is their regen.  In some cases where a fire pets physical weakness is an issue, water pets offer a solid tank taht regens quickly.  Though you must still spend mana on a ds, it is still better than spending more mana on heals (though healing fire pets is sometimes more efficient than ds'ing waters).  <br>
<br>
Earth pets are tough, but i've always hated them for experience.  They heal slowly, need to be ds'd and root mobs so they continue to fight.  Earth pets are good indoors and against tough encounters, but not for soloing outdoors/away from adds.<br>
<br>
Air pets are good for grouping imho, some people argue for their benefit against casters, and they are resistant to cold and they do interrupt and lower the damage output of mobs with stuns, but they're advantages solo are not as great as fire/water in my opinion. <br>
<br>
Try to determine the mixture needed at a camp of letting a ds'd pet take a hit vs nuking, use your resources wisely and you'll find that mages are great soloers.  At high levels we slow down, but I still outlevel my necro friend who is 53, but he can't seem to find a good spot.  <br>
<br>
